# No em dashes in prose

Do not use the em dash character (`—`, U+2014) in user-facing copy: README, docs, ADRs, `CONTEXT.md`, changelogs, JSDoc, comments, or UI strings.

When editing existing text, replace em dashes with punctuation that fits the sentence.

## Choose punctuation by role

| Role | Use | Example |
|------|-----|---------|
| Term → definition | Colon | `` `statusCode`: HTTP status `` |
| Version or label → detail | Colon | `` **1.0.0**: JSON:API is the default `` |
| Rejected option (ADRs) | Colon | `` **Keep Lerna**: rejected; … `` |
| Two related independent clauses | Semicolon | `` JSON:API by default; use plain JSON `` |
| Brief aside or contrast | Comma | `` error is truthy, either GrabkitError or … `` |
| Empty table cell | `(none)` or a word | Not an em dash placeholder |

En dashes (`–`, U+2013) are fine in compounds (`method–path`, `non–JSON:API`).

## Examples

```markdown
<!-- BAD -->
JSON:API by default — plain JSON with `format: 'json'`.
Narrow with `if (error)` — a truthy `error` means failure.
- `body` — parsed response body

<!-- GOOD -->
JSON:API by default; use plain JSON with `format: 'json'`.
Narrow with `if (error)`; a truthy `error` means failure.
- `body`: parsed response body
```

```typescript
// BAD
/** @default 'none' — passthrough; set explicitly … */

// GOOD
/** @default 'none'. Passthrough; set explicitly … */
```

Do not change em dashes inside third-party or vendored paths (e.g. `.opencode/`, `.cursor/agents/`) unless the user asks.
